 Blanco County, Colorado|Rio Blanco]]\n| 0\n| 0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Rio Grande County, Colorado|Rio Grande]]\n| 5\n| 0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Routt County, Colorado|Routt]]\n| 19\n| 0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Saguache, Colorado|Saguache]]\n| 1\n| 0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[San Juan, Colorado|San Juan]]\n| 0\n| 0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[San Miguel County, Colorado|Miguel]]\n| 4\n| 0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Sedgwick County, Colorado|Sedgwick]]\n| 0\n| 0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Summit County, Colorado|Summit]]\n| 23\n| 0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Teller County, Colorado|Teller]]\n| 7\n| 1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Washington County, Colorado|Washington]]\n| 1\n| 0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Weld County, Colorado|Weld]]\n| 293\n| 12\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Yuma County, Colorado|Yuma]]\n| 2\n| 0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |Out of State Deaths\n| \n| 1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | Unknown\n| 139\n| 0\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" |Total\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" |3342\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" |80\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [[Colorado Department of Public Health and Environment|Colorado Department of Public Health & Environment]] (CDHPE) [https://www.colorado.gov/cdphe/2019-novel-coronavirus official coronavirus page] updates, hotline phone numbers, FAQ, official media releases, links\n* [[Fort Collins Coloradoan]] - [https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/us/coronavirus-in-colorado-tracking-the-confirmed-cases-latest-news-and-updates/ar-BB10R2Gt Coronavirus in Colorado: Tracking the confirmed cases, latest news and updates]\n*Denver TV station [[KUSA-TV|9 News]] [https://www.9news.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/canceled-postponed-colorado-coronavirus/73-d67706ee-db9f-4631-8e00-b6bec07855d1 List of things canceled or postponed in Colorado due to the coronavirus]\n*Denver TV Station [[KCNC-TV|CBS 4]] [https://denver.cbslocal.com/2020/03/12/coronavirus-events-canceled-colorado-denver-postponed-list/ Coronavirus Closings: List Of Colorado Events Being Canceled Or Postponed]\n*[[Colorado Public Radio]] [https://www.cpr.org/2020/03/04/faq-got-questions-about-coronavirus-weve-got-some-answers/ coronavirus FAQ]\n*Boulder-based community radio station KGNU: [https://news.kgnu.org/2020/03/coronavirus-in-colorado-what-you-need-to-know/ Coronavirus in Colorado \u2013 What You Need To Know] includes Boulder area school closures, meal availability\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|Coronavirus disease 2019|Medicine|Pandemic|United States|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States by state|Colorado]]\n[[Category:2020 in Colorado|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Colorado]]\n[[Category:Health in Colorado]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Details of ongoing pandemic in Colorado, United States}}\n{{current event|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Colorado\n| width           = \n| image           = \n| image_size      = \n| image_upright   = \n| alt             = \n| caption         = \n| map1            = COVID-19 Cases in Colorado by counties (Density).svg\n| legend1         = Map of counties Colorado with number of confirmed cases (as of March 15){{legend|#FFE4A3|Confirmed <5}}{{legend|#F2A88D|Confirmed 6-10}}{{legend|#E57814|Confirmed 11-20}}{{legend|#FF0000|Confirmed >20}}\n| map2            = Colorado National Guard (49673441472).jpg\n| legend2         = [[Colorado Department of Public Health and Environment|CDPHE]], Colorado National Guard, and [[San Miguel County, Colorado|San Miguel County]] personnel assist at a drive-up testing center in [[Telluride, Colorado]].\n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| map4            = \n| legend4         = \n| map5            = \n| legend5         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Colorado]], U.S.\n| first_case      = [[Summit County, Colorado|Summit County]], [[Douglas County, Colorado|Douglas County]]\n| arrival_date    = March 5, 2020 ({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=03|day1=05|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}} ago)\n| origin          = [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in California|California]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Man visiting Colorado, woman in DougCo test positive for coronavirus |url=https://www.9news.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/colorado-has-first-case-of-coronavirus-covid-19/73-3d2f21d8-7969-45bc-b172-a6b0d1a1516f |website=KUSA}}</ref>\n| confirmed_cases = 3,342<ref name=\"CDPHE-official\">{{cite web|url=https://covid19.colorado.gov/data|title=Data|work=Colorado COVID-19 Updates|accessdate=2020-03-18}}</ref>\n| suspected_cases = \n| severe_cases    = \n| Hospitalized    = 620<ref name=\"CDPHE-official\"/>\n| deaths          = 80<ref name=\"CDPHE-official\"/>\n| territories     = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{URL|https://covid19.colorado.gov/}}\n}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached the U.S. state of [[Colorado]] on March 5, 2020. As of March 31, 2020, the [[Colorado Department of Public Health and Environment]] (CDPHE) confirmed 2,962 positive cases of [[COVID-19]] in the state, along with 51 deaths as a result of the disease.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.colorado.gov/pacific/cdphe/2019-novel-coronavirus|title=Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) in Colorado|date=2020-01-24|website=Department of Public Health and Environment|language=en|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref><ref name=\"CDPHE-official\" />\n\n==Timeline==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States/Colorado medical cases chart}}\n\nOn March 5, public health officials reported the first two cases of coronavirus in the state. The first case was a man in his 30s visiting [[Summit County, Colorado|Summit County]] who had made contact with a confirmed case in California.<ref>{{cite web|date=5 March 2020|access-date=5 March 2020|title=Man visiting Colorado tests positive for coronavirus|last=Johnson|first=Dacia|work=[[KUSA]]|url=https://www.9news.com/mobile/article/news/health/coronavirus/colorado-has-first-case-of-coronavirus-covid-19/73-3d2f21d8-7969-45bc-b172-a6b0d1a1516f}}</ref> The second case was an elderly woman in [[Douglas County, Colorado|Douglas County]] who had traveled internationally.<ref>{{cite web|date=5 March 2020|title=Second 'presumptive positive' Colorado coronavirus case is Douglas County woman who traveled internationally|url=https://kdvr.com/news/coronavirus/second-presumptive-positive-colorado-coronavirus-case-is-douglas-county-woman-who-traveled-internationally/|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref> Both cases were considered presumptive positives; they had been tested by the state but  had not been sent to the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]] for verification.{{Efn|The state later moved to considering presumptive positive cases as positive, without requiring additional verification from the CDC.|name=|group=}}\n\nOn March 10, Governor [[Jared Polis]] declared a state of emergency. Polis also announced 17 total presumptive positive cases in the state.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://krdo.com/news/2020/03/10/gov-jared-polis-gives-briefing-on-covid-19-with-state-health-officials/|title=Gov. Polis declares state of emergency due to COVID-19|last=Ziegler|first=Suzie|date=2020-03-10|website=KRDO|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.westword.com/news/colorado-covid-19-update-and-denver-at-possible-tipping-point-11663289|title=Polis COVID-19 Update: We May Be at Tipping Point for Spread in Denver|last=Roberts|first=Michael|date=2020-03-11|website=Westword|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref> The state announced a drive-up testing facility for patients with a doctor's note in Denver's [[Lowry, Denver|Lowry neighborhood]], at no charge to the patients.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/us/coronavirus-drive-up-testing-underway-in-denver-e2-80-99s-lowry-neighborhood/ar-BB112WbX|title=Coronavirus Drive-Up Testing Underway In Denver's Lowry Neighborhood|website=msn.com|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref>\n\nOn March 11, The [[University of Colorado Boulder]] (CU Boulder) cancelled the 72nd annual [[Conference on World Affairs]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailycamera.com/cu-boulder-cancels-conference-on-world-affairs|title=CU Boulder cancels Conference on World Affairs, citing coronavirus|date=2020-03-11|website=Boulder Daily Camera|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref> The Nederland Town Board of Trustees cancelled the annual [[Frozen Dead Guy Days]], following a Boulder County Public Health recommendation. The event was scheduled for the weekend of March 13.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.westword.com/arts/frozen-dead-guy-days-cancelled-for-2020-11663433|title=Events on Ice: Frozen Dead Guy Days Canceled|last=Calhoun|first=Patricia|date=2020-03-12|website=Westword|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref>\n\nOn March 12, a CU Boulder employee received a presumptive positive test for COVID-19. The employee worked on March 9 from 8 a.m. to noon in limited areas of the Center for Community dining center.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailycamera.com/cu-boulder-confirms-employee-tested-presumptive-positive-for-covid-19|title=CU Boulder confirms employee tested presumptive positive for COVID-19|date=2020-03-12|website=Boulder Daily Camera|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref> Despite Boulder County health's recommendations, the annual May [[Bolder Boulder]] race and the Boulder Creek Festival were still scheduled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailycamera.com/boulder-county-health-recommends-canceling-bolder-boulder-creek-fest|title=Boulder County health recommends canceling Bolder Boulder, Creek Fest|date=2020-03-12|website=Broomfield Enterprise|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref> Many major school districts, including [[Denver Public Schools]], [[Jefferson County Public Schools (Colorado)|Jefferson County Public Schools]] and [[Cherry Creek Public Schools]], announced closures lasting at least two weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.denverpost.com/2020/03/11/colorado-schools-closed-coronavirus/|title=Colorado schools closed because of coronavirus|date=March 11, 2020}}</ref>  Due to the current strain on medical facilities in mountain communities, Govenor [[Jared Polis]] discouraged mountain travel for the elderly.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.denverpost.com/2020/03/13/colorado-coronavirus-response-school-closures/|title=As schools close, Colorado prepares to shift coronavirus response to focus on softening impacts|date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 13, Colorado reported its first COVID-19-related death: an 80-year-old woman with underlying health issues from [[El Paso County, Colorado|El Paso County]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://coloradosun.com/2020/03/13/colorado-coronavirus-death-announced/|title=Colorado announces its first death from the coronavirus|last=Paul|first=Jesse|date=2020-03-13|website=The Colorado Sun|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.colorado.gov/pacific/cdphe/news/colorado-has-first-death-covid-19-el-paso-county|title=Colorado has first death from COVID-19 in El Paso County|date=March 13, 2020|website=Department of Public Health and Environment|access-date=March 14, 2020}}</ref> To offset the loss of quarantined medical personnel, Govenor [[Jared Polis]] asked former doctors and nurses to rejoin the stressed medical workforce.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/new-york-colorado-governors-call-on-former-doctors-nurses-to-rejoin-workforce-amid-coronavirus-pandemic/|title=New York, Colorado governors call on \"former\" doctors, nurses to rejoin workforce amid coronavirus pandemic|website=cbsnews.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref> Due to low temperatures, the Lowry drive-up testing service did not operate. The state planned to move the drive-up testing to the [[Denver Coliseum]], starting March 14, subject to weather. The testing at the Coliseum would service a maximum of 150 patients. The [[Colorado Department of Public Health and Environment]] (CDPHE) also planned to move the drive-up service to strategic locations as warranted.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.denverpost.com/2020/03/13/denver-drive-thru-coronavirus-closes-weather/|title=Colorado's drive-thru coronavirus lab will move to the Denver Coliseum|date=2020-03-13|website=The Denver Post|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref> In [[Aspen, Colorado|Aspen]], 10 Australian ski vacationers were confirmed with the virus, with three others refusing testing. The three Australians who refused testing were quarantined for two weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/australians-in-colorado-refuse-test-for-virus-despite-confirmed-cases-20200314-p54a08.html|title=Australians in Colorado refuse test for virus despite confirmed cases|last=Bourke|first=Latika|date=2020-03-13|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref>\n\nOn March 14, the state legislature went into recess for two weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://coloradosun.com/2020/03/13/colorado-capitol-recess-coronavirus-coronavirus/|title=Colorado legislature will shut down on Saturday for 2 weeks because of coronavirus|last=Paul|first=Jesse|last2=Frank|first2=John|date=2020-03-13|website=The Colorado Sun|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.denverpost.com/2020/03/13/coronavirus-colorado-legislature-shutdown/|title=Coronavirus pandemic shuts down Colorado Capitol for at least two weeks|date=2020-03-13|website=The Denver Post|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref> Govenor [[Jared Polis]] issued an executive order to close downhill ski areas for a week, doing so \"with a profound sense of pain and grim responsibility.\" Some ski areas had already planned to close on March 15.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://coloradosun.com/2020/03/14/jared-polis-executive-order-ski-resorts/|title=Colorado governor orders all ski resorts to close for at least a week in extraordinary move|website=The Colorado Sun|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.9news.com/article/news/local/colorado-ski-resorts-closing-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/73-7fa49e14-69b0-47f9-acb6-529d34341445|title=Gov. Polis issues executive order closing all Colorado ski areas for one week|website=KUSA|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://gazette.com/news/gov-polis-orders-colorado-ski-resorts-to-temporarily-close/article_7c3874b8-6658-11ea-bbc7-379298093ba5.html|title=Gov. Polis orders Colorado ski resorts to temporarily close|last=Boster|first=Seth|date=2020-03-14|website=Colorado Springs Gazette|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.denverpost.com/2020/03/15/new-coronavirus-cases-colorado/|title=Coronavirus cases in Colorado rise to 131|date=2020-03-15|website=The Denver Post|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\nOn March 16, [[Michael Hancock (Colorado politician)|Denver Mayor Hancock]] ordered all bars and restaurants closed by 8 a.m. on March 17 (except for food delivery and pickup) and banned gatherings of more than 50 people.<ref name=\"CO_mar16\">{{cite news |last1=Oravetz |first1=Janet |title=All Denver restaurants and bars ordered to close to indoor dining for 8 weeks |url=https://www.9news.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/denver-coronavirus-update/73-e04fa1e5-bf55-443a-83ed-6fb3e9d02dcc |accessdate=16 March 2020 |publisher=NBC - 9News}}</ref> Govenor [[Jared Polis]] expanded the closures by ordering a state-wide closure of dine-in services, gyms, casinos, and theaters.<ref name=\"CO_mar16_polis\">{{cite news |last1=Wingerter |first1=Meg |title=Colorado governor orders bars, restaurants to halt dine-in service statewide in fight against coronavirus |url=https://www.denverpost.com/2020/03/16/coronavirus-colorado-bars-restaurants-dmv-closed/ |accessdate=17 March 2020 |agency=The Denver Post |publisher=The Denver Post}}</ref>\n\nOn March 18, Govenor [[Jared Polis]] closed schools until April 17 and banned gatherings of more than 10 people for the following 30 days. Polis also ordered ski resorts to remain closed until April 6.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cpr.org/2020/03/18/polis-closes-all-of-colorados-schools-until-at-least-april-17/|title=Polis Closes All Of Colorado's Schools Until April 17, Bans Gatherings of More Than 10 People|last=Birkeland|first=Bente|date=2020-03-18|work=Colorado Public Radio|accessdate=2020-03-19}}</ref> The governor also expressed frustration with nonchalance regarding [[social distancing]] and announced the creation of a fund to aid Coloradans affected by COVID-19.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cpr.org/2020/03/18/polis-to-coloradans-please-dont-be-stupid/|title=\"Please Don't Be Stupid,\" Polis Says To Coloradans, About The Coronavirus|last=Colorado Public Radio Staff|date=2020-03-18|work=Colorado Public Radio|accessdate=2020-03-19}}</ref> [[San Miguel County, Colorado|San Miguel County]] became the first county in the nation to plan to test all of its residents. It also ordered residents to \"shelter-in-place.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kktv.com/content/news/San-Miguel-County-shelter-in-place-orders-will-be-1st-in-US-to-test-entire-County-with-UBIs-blood-test-568914371.html|title=San Miguel County shelter-in-place orders, will be 1st in U.S. to test entire County with UBI's blood test|date=2020-03-18|work=KKTV 11 News|accessdate=2020-03-20}}</ref> Gun sales skyrocket in Colorado, along with toilet paper, and hand sanitizer, thousands of Coloradians are also falling in line with the national trend of stocking up on guns.<ref>https://denver.cbslocal.com/2020/03/18/coronavirus-colorado-guns-ammunition/</ref>\n\nOn March 19, Colorado reported two more COVID-19-related deaths, one of which was a man related to Colorado's first death.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.denverpost.com/2020/03/19/coronavirus-third-death-el-paso-county/|title=2 new coronavirus-related deaths reported in Colorado as confirmed cases rise to 277|last=Tabachnik|first=Sam|date=2020-03-19|work=The Denver Post|accessdate=2020-03-20}}</ref> Govenor [[Jared Polis]] extended the closure of bars, restaurants, theaters, gymnasiums and casinos until April 30 and suspended all nonessential medical procedures. The governor also ordered the closure of \"nonessential\" businesses until April 30, which include nail salons, spas, and tattoo parlors.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.denverpost.com/2020/03/19/coronavirus-hospital-procedures-restaurant-bar-closure-colorado/|title=Polis suspends all nonessential medical procedures in Colorado, extends restaurant and bar closure to April 30|last=Zalubowski|first=David|date=2020-03-19|work=The Denver Post|accessdate=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\nOn March 21, [[Rocky Mountain National Park]] closed after the mayor of [[Estes Park, Colorado|Estes Park]] cited concerns about the novel coronavirus.<ref>{{Cite news| last = Meyer| first = John| title = Rocky Mountain National Park closes amid coronavirus outbreak at the request of mayor, local health department| work = The Denver Post| date = 2020-03-20 |url=https://www.denverpost.com/2020/03/20/rocky-mountain-national-park-closes-coronavirus-estes-park/}}</ref>\n\nOn March 23, Aytu BioScience, a pharmaceutical company in Colorado, announced that it developed a blood test that will deliver results in two to ten minutes at the point of care for antibodies for the COVID-19 virus. The FDA has now approved the test for distribution.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://patch.com/colorado/littleton/colorado-company-develops-rapid-test-new-coronavirus|title=Colorado Company Develops Rapid Test For New Coronavirus|date=Mar 23, 2020|website=Littleton, CO Patch|accessdate=Mar 26, 2020}}</ref> [[Michael Hancock (Colorado politician)|Denver Mayor Hancock]] announced a \"stay at home\" order for Denver county. This was to go into effect Tuesday March 24 at 5pm.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://denverite.com/2020/03/23/heres-what-denvers-new-stay-at-home-orders-mean/|title=Here's what Denver's new stay at home orders mean|date=Mar 23, 2020|accessdate=Mar 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 24, thirteen Colorado counties and multiple cities had announced some form of stay-at-home order, including Adams County, Arapahoe County, Archuleta County, Boulder County, Broomfield County, Denver County, Douglas County, Eagle County, Grand County, Jefferson County, La Plata County, Pitkin County and San Miguel County.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kdvr.com/news/coronavirus/list-all-of-the-colorado-counties-with-stay-at-home-orders/|title=List: All the Colorado cities and counties that have announced stay-at-home orders|date=Mar 24, 2020|accessdate=Mar 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 25, Govenor [[Jared Polis]] put the state of Colorado in complete lock-down, with a [[stay-at-home order]]. This started on Thursday the 26th at six am and was scheduled to last through April 11.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cpr.org/2020/03/25/polis-announces-statewide-stay-at-home-order/|title=Polis Issues Colorado Stay-at-Home Order: 'Now Is Not The Time To Die'|first=Colorado Public Radio|last=Staff|website=Colorado Public Radio|accessdate=Mar 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 26 Mike Willis, Colorado's director of emergency management, had a new coronavirus testing program for health care workers, and first responders. The state had received 5,000 test kits, with another 2,500 expected in the following week. \"The state is setting up test locations \u2014 one each in the north, south and on the Western Slope, Willis said. Exact testing location times and places have not been announced.\" [[Colorado Parks and Wildlife]] will be closing all playgrounds, campgrounds, camping and camping facilities \u2014 including yurts and cabins \u2014 at Colorado's state parks as well as camping at State Wildlife Areas until further notice.<ref>{{cite web|last=Tabachnik |first=Sam |url=https://www.denverpost.com/2020/03/26/colorado-coronavirus-testing-health-care-workers-first-responders/ |title=Coronavirus testing program for health care workers, first responders in Colorado |publisher=Denverpost.com |date=2020-03-26 |accessdate=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\nOn March 27 Govenor [[Jared Polis]] said that he is working to add 5,000 ICU beds to Colorado's capacity by the end of the summer and is in conversations to bring more ventilators to the state to treat sick COVID-19 patients.<ref name=\"news1\">{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.9news.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/blog-tracking-coronavirus-updates-colorado-march-30/73-3285ce99-295b-4beb-a277-79e57f046d49 |title=Coronavirus latest updates in Colorado: March 30 |publisher=9news.com |date= |accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\nOn March 28, President [[Donald Trump]] Approves Colorado Disaster Declaration.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefings-statements/president-donald-j-trump-approves-colorado-disaster-declaration/ |title=President Donald J. Trump Approves Colorado Disaster Declaration &#124; The White House |publisher=Whitehouse.gov |date=2020-01-20 |accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref> Governor [[Jared Polis]] announced that President Trump had approved the request to declare a major disaster for Colorado. The status means the state is eligible to receive additional federal resources and funding to help address the pandemic.<ref name=\"news1\"/> the ''[[New York Post]]'' named [[Gunnison County]], at 454.20 per 100,000 people and [[Eagle County]] at 331.74 per 100,000<ref>{{cite web|url=https://covid19.colorado.gov/case-data |title=Case data &#124; Colorado COVID-19 Updates |publisher=Covid19.colorado.gov |date= |accessdate=2020-03-30}}</ref> as being two of the top four counties leading the nation in confirmed cases outside of New York and Louisiana. The other two counties are [[Blaine County, Idaho]] and [[Summit County, Utah]]. They state that this will no doubt overwhelm local hospitals.<ref>{{cite web|last=Connelly |first=Eileen AJ |url=https://nypost.com/2020/03/28/coronavirus-cases-climb-in-rural-us-cities-popular-with-tourists/ |title=Coronavirus cases climb in rural US cities popular with tourists |publisher=Nypost.com |date=1970-01-01 |accessdate=2020-03-30}}</ref> Andy Larson of the ''[[Salt Lake Tribune]]'' did some math based on factual reporting, and put [[Gunnison County]], Colorado third in the country for cases per capita. He listed [[Eagle County]] as eighth.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sltrib.com/news/2020/03/28/andy-larsen-so-just-how/|title=Andy Larsen: So just how bad is it in Summit County? Here's what the coronavirus numbers show.|website=The Salt Lake Tribune}}</ref>\n\nOn March 29, CDOT, [[Colorado Department of Transportation]], suspended the [[Bustang]] and Outrider through at least April 11.<ref>{{cite web|last=Bradbury |first=Shelly |url=https://www.denverpost.com/2020/03/29/cdot-bustang-outrider-suspended-colorado-coronavirus/ |title=CDOT suspends Bustang, Outrider bus service in Colorado due to coronavirus |publisher=Denverpost.com |date= 29 March 2020|accessdate=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\nOn March 31, [[Gunnison County]] announced they will begin working with a company called Biobot, to test fecal samples from the sewer system, to track coronavirus.\nThe county will collect samples and send them back to Biobot which can produce results in about three days.  The tests will help measure the scope of the outbreak in the county, and track the impact of interventions, such as social distancing. It could also act as an early warning system for a re-emergence of cases.<ref>https://www.thedenverchannel.com/news/local-news/gunnison-county-will-test-fecal-samples-from-sewer-system-to-track-coronavirus</ref> Colorado Doctors are turning to telemedicine, to keep people out of the hospitals or ERs where their chance at infection of COVID-19 is higher. Many Health insurance companies will pay the Doctors the same rate for a virtual visit as in-person. Previously insurance compainies only paid about half as much. Also, Medicare may wave co-payments on these visits. So, this is an affordable way to maintain the spread of infection.<ref>https://www.denverpost.com/2020/03/31/colorado-telemedicine-coronavirus/</ref> The demand for guns in Colorado continues to rise amid the novel coronavirus pandemic. Despite the CBI strongly encouraging firearm dealers to hold firearms until the background checks are completed, gun shops are considered essential businesses under the state's stay-at-home order and are classified as \u201ccritical retail,\u201d along with grocery stores, gas stations, marijuana and liquor stores, and several other businesses.<ref>https://www.denverpost.com/2020/03/31/colorado-gun-sales-coronavirus/</ref> Mike Wills, director of the state's Office of Emergency Management, said that, [[Budweiser Events Center]] could serve as a temporary hospital as Colorado prepares for the coronavirus surge.<ref>https://www.denverpost.com/2020/03/31/coronavirus-colorado-hospital-capacity-borders/</ref>\n\nAt the end of March, the [[United States Air Force Academy]] in [[Colorado Springs]] eased some of its social distancing measures for its on-campus cadets, after two seniors committed suicide there in the prior week. Earlier strict efforts to isolate and separate cadets had provoked complaints.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Roeder |first1=Tom |title=Air Force Academy relaxes rules, focuses on cadet mental health after suicides |url=https://gazette.com/military/air-force-academy-relaxes-rules-focuses-on-cadet-mental-health-after-suicides/article_6272dfb6-7358-11ea-8d46-1b5c929243b4.html |accessdate=1 April 2020 |publisher=The Gazette |date=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 1, Colorado readies guidelines for prioritizing coronavirus patient care if hospitals overload. With the latest tally on Tuesday, of 3,342 cases, and 620 people hospitalized with COVID-19<ref>https://covid19.colorado.gov/case-data</ref>, Julie Lonborg a spokeswoman for the Colorado Hospital Association, said the state's medical network at the moment \"not anywhere near capacity\". We've seen in other states and countries that there can be a lot of patients all at once. That kind of surge could force doctors to have to decide which critical patients get scarce equipment and staffing to keep them alive.<ref>https://www.denverpost.com/2020/03/30/coronavirus-overwhelmed-hospitals-priorities/</ref> About the new guideline, Dr. [[Matthew Wynia]], director of the Center for Bioethics and Humanities at the CU Anschutz Medical Campus said, \u201cThis is statewide guidance on how to do triage in the most ethically defensible way,\u201d <ref>https://www.denverpost.com/2020/04/01/colorado-hospital-capacity-coronavirus-covid/</ref> The Seattle-based Institute for Health Metrics and Evaluation projects that Colorado will hit its peak COVID-19 cases on April 17, when it says there could be a shortage of nearly 2,000 hospital beds and nearly 500 intensive care unit beds based on the measures the state has taken so far to stem the spread of the virus. A number of efforts are underway to close that gap.<ref>https://covid19.healthdata.org/projections</ref>\n\n==Government response==\nOn March 10, Govenor [[Jared Polis]] declared a state of emergency, ordering the state's Department of Labor and Employment to develop rules for requiring employees in sectors such as food service and health care be offered paid sick leave if they display symptoms.<ref name=\"The Colorado Sun\">{{cite web|date=10 March 2020|access-date=10 March 2020|title=Gov. Jared Polis declares state of emergency in response to coronavirus outbreak|work=[[The Colorado Sun]]|last1=Ingold|first1=John|last2=Paul|first2=Jesse|url=https://coloradosun.com/2020/03/10/colorado-state-of-emergency-coronavirus-jared-polis/|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310202821/https://coloradosun.com/2020/03/10/colorado-state-of-emergency-coronavirus-jared-polis/|archive-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref> The March 14 executive order to close ski areas for a week was the second most significant action by the governor.<ref name=\"The Colorado Sun\"/>\n\nOn March 22, Govenor [[Jared Polis]] ordered non-essential businesses to reduce the number of people physically present in the workplace by 50 percent, and more if possible.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cpr.org/2020/03/22/colorado-coronavirus-update-polis-work-from-home-order/|title=Polis Says State Won't Enforce Social Distancing But 'Grim Reaper' Will, As State Orders More Working From Home|first1=Dave|last1=Burdick|first2=Kate|last2=Schimel|website=Colorado Public Radio|accessdate=Mar 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Self-quarantine of government officials ===\nOn March 17, both [[Cory Gardner|Senator Cory Gardner]] and [[Jason Crow|Representative Jason Crow]] elected to self-quarantine for 14 days, until March 25. Both Gardner and Crow interacted with a Coloradan who tested positive for COVID-19 on March 11. The legislators represented two of 14 members of the [[United States Congress|U.S. Congress]] who decided to self-quarantine.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.coloradopolitics.com/quick-hits/u-s-sen-cory-gardner-to-self-quarantine-following-contact/article_1fcbd7d2-68a7-11ea-97a3-2392673a2321.html|title=U.S. Sen. Cory Gardner to self-quarantine following contact with infected Coloradan|last=Luning|first=Ernest|date=2020-03-17|work=Colorado Politics|accessdate=2020-03-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.coloradopolitics.com/coronavirus/u-s-rep-jason-crow-to-self-quarantine-after-coronavirus/article_2856c624-68ba-11ea-b567-abff91d46857.html|title=U.S. Rep. Jason Crow to self-quarantine after coronavirus contact|last=Luning|first=Ernest|date=2020-03-17|work=Colorado Politics|accessdate=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\nOn March 19, Colorado State Rep. [[Dafna Michaelson Jenet]] reported testing positive for coronavirus. Michaelson Jenet was the first member of the [[Colorado General Assembly]] to report testing positive for coronavirus, and elected to self-quarantine in her home. Michaelson Jenet was at the [[Colorado Capitol]] on March 14, the day it closed due to the virus.<ref>{{cite web| last = Paul| first = Jesse| title = Colorado lawmaker tests positive for coronavirus, has mild symptoms| work = The Colorado Sun| accessdate = 2020-03-19| date = 2020-03-19| url = https://coloradosun.com/2020/03/19/dafna-michaelson-jenet-positive-colorado-coronavirus/}}</ref>\n\n==Impact on sports==\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports}}\nMost of state's sports teams were affected. Several leagues began postponing or suspending their seasons starting March 12. [[Major League Baseball]] cancelled the remainder of [[spring training]] on that date, and on March 16, they announced that the season will be postponed indefinitely, after the recommendations from the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]] to restrict events of more than 50 people for the next eight weeks, affecting the [[2020 Colorado Rockies season|Colorado Rockies]].<ref name=\"mlb\">{{cite web |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/opening-of-regular-season-to-be-pushed-back |title=Opening of regular season to be pushed back |first=Mark |last=Feinsand |website=[[MLB.com]] |date=March 16, 2020 |access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> Also on March 12, the [[National Basketball Association]] announced the season would be suspended for 30 days, affecting the [[2019\u201320 Denver Nuggets season|Denver Nuggets]].<ref name=nba>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28893331/nba-owners-seeking-30-day-reevaluation-suspension-games |title=Silver: NBA hiatus likely to last 'at least' 30 days |date=March 12, 2020 |website=ESPN.com |language=en|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Colorado Avalanche===\nThe [[2019\u201320 Colorado Avalanche season]] was suspended for an indefinite amount of time as the [[National Hockey League]] suspended the season.<ref name=nhl>[https://www.nhl.com/news/nhl-coronavirus-status/c-316155530 NHL statement on coronavirus] NHL, March 12, 2020</ref> After a player on the [[Ottawa Senators]] tested positive for coronavirus on {{date|March 17}}, concerns arose about the Avalanche's potential exposure. The Avalanche used the [[San Jose Sharks]]' locker room after the Senators.<ref>{{cite web| last = Chambers| first = Mike| title = Avalanche might have been exposed to coronavirus in San Jose| work = The Denver Post| accessdate = 2020-03-19| date = 2020-03-18| url = https://www.denverpost.com/2020/03/18/colorado-avalanche-san-jose-sharks-nhl-coronavirus/}}</ref>\n\n===College sports===\nIn college sports, the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] cancelled all winter and spring tournaments, most notably the [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] [[2020 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|men]]'s and [[2020 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|women]]'s basketball tournaments, affecting colleges and universities statewide.<ref name=ncaa>[https://www.ncaa.org/about/resources/media-center/news/ncaa-cancels-remaining-winter-and-spring-championships NCAA cancels remaining winter and spring championships] NCAA, March 12, 2020</ref> On March 16, the [[National Junior College Athletic Association]] also canceled the remainder of the winter seasons as well as the spring seasons.<ref>[https://www.mlive.com/sports/2020/03/njcaa-cancels-spring-sports-basketball-nationals-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html NJCAA cancels spring sports, basketball nationals amid coronavirus outbreak] MLive.com, March 16, 2020</ref>\n\n== Controversies ==\n\n=== Testing capacity and timing ===\nDespite the urgency for testing Coloradans for COVID-19, many people have been frustrated with the state's limited testing capacity and slow response time.<ref name=\"frustrations\">{{cite web|url=https://kdvr.com/news/coronavirus/frustrations-rise-over-few-coronavirus-testing-options-in-colorado/|title=Frustrations rise over few coronavirus testing options in Colorado|last=Low|first=Rob|date=2020-03-19|work=FOX31 Denver|accessdate=2020-03-19}}</ref> Govenor [[Jared Polis]] has noted that expanding testing capacity is \"absolutely critical\", yet limited supplies and a small number of trained medical staff have resulted in a low testing rate.<ref name=\"frustrations\" /> While CDPHE implemented a mobile testing site in [[Lowry, Denver]] (later moved to the Denver Colosseum), the site closed due to long lines.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kdvr.com/news/coronavirus/drive-up-coronavirus-test-lab-in-denver-metro-remains-closed/|title=Drive-Up coronavirus test lab in Denver metro remains closed|last=Allen|first=Emily|date=2020-03-17|work=FOX31 Denver|accessdate=2020-03-19}}</ref> As of March 18, no private laboratories were performing tests<ref name=\"frustrations\" /> and only people who exhibited the most severe symptoms were being prioritized for testing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thedenverchannel.com/news/coronavirus/colorado-covid-19-tests-prioritized-for-most-at-risk-health-care-workers-state-launches-new-tracking-site|title=Colorado COVID-19 tests prioritized for most at-risk & health care workers; state launches new tracking site|last=Miller|first=Blair|date=2020-03-18|work=KMGH|accessdate=2020-03-19}}</ref> While some tests can be completed in a matter of minutes, Colorado's test results have taken up to five days.<ref name=\"frustrations\" />\n\n== Statistics ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:right\"\n! colspan=\"3\" |2019 Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) Cases in Colorado<ref>{{cite web| title = Data| work = Colorado COVID-19 Updates| accessdate = 2020-03-18| url = https://covid19.colorado.gov/data}}</ref>\nUpdated {{date|April 1, 2020}}\n<!-- As of March 17, CDPHE released their data online: https://data-cdphe.opendata.arcgis.com/datasets/colorado-covid-19-positive-cases-and-rates-of-infection-by-county-of-identification . This should be considered the authoritative source and should be used to update this table. -->\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | County\n! scope=\"col\" | Confirmed Cases\n! scope=\"col\" | Deaths\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Adams County, Colorado|Adams]]\n| 212\n| 2\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Alamosa County, Colorado|Alamosa]]\n| 4\n| 0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Arapahoe County, Colorado|Arapahoe]]\n| 381\n| 7\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Archuleta County, Colorado|Archuleta]]\n| 1\n| 0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Baca County, Colorado|Baca]]\n| 3\n| 0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Bent County, Colorado|Bent]]\n| 0\n| 0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Boulder County, Colorado|Boulder]]\n| 114\n| 2\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Broomfield County, Colorado|Broomfield]]\n| 21\n| 2\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Chaffee County, Colorado|Chaffee]]\n| 17\n| 1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Cheyenne County, Colorado|Cheyenne]]\n| 0\n| 0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Clear Creek County, Colorado|Clear Creek]]\n| 6\n| 0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Conejos County, Colorado|Conejos]]\n| 0\n| 0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Costilla County, Colorado|Costilla]]\n| 3\n| 0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Crowley County, Colorado|Crowley]]\n| 1\n| 1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Custer County, Colorado|Custer]]\n| 0\n| 0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Delta County, Colorado|Delta]]\n| 1\n| 0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Denver]]\n| 586\n| 8\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Dolores County, Colorado|Dolores]]\n| 0\n| 0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Douglas County, Colorado|Douglas]]\n| 158\n| 0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Eagle County, Colorado|Eagle]]\n| 295\n| 4\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[El Paso County, Colorado|El Paso]]\n| 314\n| 14\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Elbert County, Colorado|Elbert]]\n| 5\n| 0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Fremont County, Colorado|Fremont]]\n| 2\n| 0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Garfield County, Colorado|Garfield]]\n| 34\n| 1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Gilpin County, Colorado|Gilpin]]\n| 0\n| 0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Grand County, Colorado|Grand]]\n| 4\n| 0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Gunnison County, Colorado|Gunnison]]\n| 84\n| 1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Hinsdale County, Colorado|Hinsdale]]\n| 1\n| 0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Huerfano County, Colorado|Huerfano]]\n| 1\n| 0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Jackson County, Colorado|Jackson]]\n| 0\n| 0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Jefferson County, Colorado|Jefferson]]\n| 356\n| 7\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Kiowa County, Colorado|Kiowa]]\n| 0\n| 0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Kit Carson, Colorado|Kit Carson]]\n| 4\n| 0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[La Plata County, Colorado|La Plata]]\n| 23\n| 0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Lake County, Colorado|Lake]]\n| 2\n| 0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Larimer County, Colorado|Larimer]]\n| 107\n| 7\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Las Animas County, Colorado|Las Animas]]\n| 0\n| 0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Lincoln County, Colorado|Lincoln]]\n| 1\n| 0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Logan County, Colorado|Logan]]\n|